    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "Using the eight time dependences e \u2212\u0393t (1+Ci cos \u2206mt+Si sin \u2206mt) for the decays \u03a5 (4S) \u2192 B 0 B 0 \u2192 fjf k , with the decay into a flavor-specific state fj = \u2113 \u00b1 X before or after the decay into a CP eigenstate f k = ccKS,L, as measured by the BABAR experiment, we determine the three CP Tsensitive parameters Re (z) and Im (z) in B 0 -B 0 mixing and |A/A| in B 0 \u2192 ccK 0 decays. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "We find Im (z) = 0.010 \u00b1 0.030 \u00b1 0.013, Re (z) = \u22120.065 \u00b1 0.028 \u00b1 0.014, and |A/A| = 0.999 \u00b1 0.023 \u00b1 0.017, in agreement with CP T symmetry. ",
            "paragraph_rank": 1,
            "section_rank": 1
        },
        {
            "text": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The discovery of CP violation in 1964 [1] motivated searches for T and CP T violation. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 38,
                    "end": 41,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b13",
                    "text": "[1]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Since CP T = CP \u00d7T , violation of CP means that T or CP T or both are also violated. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "For the K 0 system, the two contributions were first determined [2] in 1970, by using the Bell-Steinberger unitarity relation [3] for CP violation in K 0 -K 0 mixing: T was violated with about 5\u03c3 significance and no CP T violation was observed. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 64,
                    "end": 67,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b14",
                    "text": "[2]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 129,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b15",
                    "text": "[3]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Large CP violation in the B 0 system was discovered in 2001 [4,5] in the interplay of B 0 -B 0 mixing and B 0 \u2192 ccK 0 decays, but an explicit demonstration of T violation was given only recently [6]. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 60,
                    "end": 63,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b16",
                    "text": "[4,"
                },
                {
                    "start": 63,
                    "end": 65,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b17",
                    "text": "5]"
                },
                {
                    "start": 195,
                    "end": 198,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b18",
                    "text": "[6]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "In the present analysis, we test CP T symmetry quantitavely in B 0 -B 0 mixing and in B 0 \u2192ccK 0 decays.",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 2,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Transitions in the B 0 -B 0 system are well described by the quantum-mechanical evolution of a two-state wavefunction",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 3,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "using the Schr\u00f6dinger equatio\u1e45",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 4,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "where the Hamiltonian H is given by two constant Hermitian matrices, H ij = m ij + i\u0393 ij /2. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "In this evolution, CP violation is described by three parameters, |q/p|, Re (z), and Im (z), defined by",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 5,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "where",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 6,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "are the mass and the width differences of the two mass eigenstates (H=heavy, L=light) of the Hamiltonian, Note that we use the convention with +q for the light and \u2212q for the heavy eigenstate. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "If |q/p| = 1, the evolution violates the discrete symmetries CP and T . ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "If z = 0, it violates CP and CP T . ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The normalizations of the two eigenstates, as given in Eq. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "4, are precise in the lowest order of r and z, where r = |q/p| \u2212 1. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 0,
                    "end": 1,
                    "ref_id": "formula_4",
                    "text": "4"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Throughout the following, we neglect contributions of orders r 2 , z 2 , r z, and higher.",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 7,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "The T -sensitive mixing parameter |q/p| has been determined in several experiments, the present world average [7] being |q/p| = 1 + (0.8 \u00b1 0.8) \u00d7 10 \u22123 . ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 110,
                    "end": 113,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b19",
                    "text": "[7]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "The CP T -sensitive parameter Im (z) has been determined by analyzing the time dependence of di-lepton events in the decay \u03a5 (4S) \u2192 B 0 B 0 \u2192 (\u2113 + \u03bdX) (\u2113 \u2212 \u03bdX); the BABAR result [8] is Im (z) = (\u221213.9 \u00b1 7.3 \u00b1 3.2) \u00d7 10 \u22123 . ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 178,
                    "end": 181,
                    "type": "bibr",
                    "ref_id": "b20",
                    "text": "[8]"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "text": "Since \u2206\u0393 is very small, di-lepton events are only sensitive to the product Re (z)\u2206\u0393. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "Therefore, Re (z) has so far only been determined by analyzing the time dependence of the decays \u03a5 (4S) \u2192 B 0 B 0 with one B meson decaying into \u2113\u03bdX and the other one into ccK. ",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2
        },
        {
            "text": "With 88 \u00d7 10 6 BB events, BABAR measured Re (z) = (19 \u00b1 48 \u00b1 47) \u00d7 10 \u22123 in 2004 [9], while Belle used 535 \u00d7 10 6 BB events to measure Re (z) = (19 \u00b1 37 \u00b1 33) \u00d7 10 \u22123 in 2012 [10].",
            "section": "I. INTRODUCTION",
            "paragraph_rank": 8,
            "section_rank": 2,
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 81,
